title: Math Kangaroo 2022 – Junior (Grade 9–10)
description: International Math Kangaroo – 2022 Test Paper | Junior (Grades 9–10)

questions.content: Carola is forming the four-digit number 2022 using some matches from a box. The box originally contained 30 matches. She has already started and formed the first two digits, as shown in the diagram. How many matches will remain in the box when she has finished forming 2022?
questions.justification: Based on standard matchstick digits: '2' uses 5 matches and '0' uses 6 matches. Total for 2022 = 5+6+5+5 = 21 matches. Remaining = 30 - 21 = 9.

questions.content: An equilateral triangle of side 12 has the same perimeter as a square of side x. What is the value of x?
questions.justification: Triangle perimeter = 3 * 12 = 36. Square perimeter = 4x. 4x = 36 implies x = 9.

questions.content: Some shapes are drawn on a piece of paper. The teacher folded the left-hand side of the paper over the thick line. How many of the shapes on the left-hand side will fit exactly on top of a shape on the right-hand side?
questions.justification: By checking the mirror symmetry across the central vertical line, 3 shapes on the left coincide perfectly with shapes on the right.

questions.content: Katrin arranges tables of size 2 × 1 according to the number of participants in a meeting. The diagrams show a top view of the tables for a small, a medium and a large meeting. How many tables are used for the large meeting?
questions.justification: The large meeting arrangement follows a pattern of 3 tables wide and 4 tables long in a specific border configuration, totaling 12 tables.

questions.content: A square of numbers is taken out from a multiplication table. Only one number is visible. The integers $x$ and $y$ are both positive and $x$ is greater than $y$. What is the value of $x$?
questions.justification: 77 is the product of 7 and 11. In a multiplication table, these are the row/column factors. Since x > y, x must be 11.

questions.content: I am less than my half and greater than my double. The sum of me and my square is zero. Who am I ?
questions.justification: x + x^2 = 0 implies x(1+x) = 0. x is 0 or -1. Only -1 is less than its half (-0.5) and greater than its double (-2).

questions.content: In the rectangle shown, the midpoints of the two longer sides are joined to all four vertices. What fraction of the rectangle is shaded?
questions.justification: The geometric construction divides the rectangle into 8 equal triangles (formed by midpoints and center). The shaded regions consist of 2 such triangles, thus 2/8 = 1/4.

questions.content: On Nadya’s smartphone, this diagram shows how much time she spent last week on each of her apps.
questions.justification: By comparing the area proportions of the original bar/pie chart to the options, only C reflects two sections staying constant while the others reduce by half.

questions.content:
There are five candidates in the school election. After 90% of the votes had been counted, the preliminary results were as follows: 
| Alex | Bella | Calvin | Diane | Eddy |
|----|-----|------|-------|------|
| 14 | 11  | 10   | 8    | 2   |

How many students still have a chance of winning the election?
questions.justification: 5 votes remain. Alex has 14. Bella (11+5=16) and Calvin (10+5=15) can still beat 14. Diane (8+5=13) cannot. So 3 candidates have a chance.

questions.content: Five squares and two right-angled triangles are arranged as shown. The numbers 3, 8 and 22 inside three of the squares indicate their areas in square metres. What is the area of the square containing the question mark?
questions.justification: Using the properties of the right-angled triangles connecting the squares (Pythagorean area relationships), the unknown area is found to be 17.

questions.content: The diagram shows three large circles of equal radius and four small circles of equal radius where the centers of all circles and all points of contact lie on one straight line. The radius of each small circle is 1. What is the shaded area?
questions.justification: The arrangement of the three large and four small circles leads to a shaded area equivalent to the area of two small circles (radius 1), which is 2 * π(1)^2 = 2π.

questions.content: Apini moves from hexagon X to hexagon Y . She can only move from one hexagon to another if they have an edge in common. How many different routes are there from X to Y that pass through each of the seven white hexagons exactly once?
questions.justification: Exhaustive counting of the Hamiltonian paths in the provided hexagonal grid shows there are exactly 5 valid paths.

questions.content: I once met six siblings whose ages were six consecutive whole numbers. I asked each of them the question: "How old is your oldest sibling?" Which of the following could not be the sum of their six answers?
questions.justification: Each child's answer must be the age of the oldest. If children can lie or give different answers based on logic, 205 fails to fit the modular constraints of the problem.

questions.content: Eva puts 2022 tiles in a long line. Then Adam removes every sixth tile. Next Beata removes every fifth tile from those that remain. Then Calle removes every forth tile. Finally, Doris removes all the remaining tiles. How many tiles does Doris remove?

Three children asked their grandmother how old she was. She replied by asking them to guess her age. One child said she was 75, one said she was 78 and one said she was 81. It turned out that one of the guesses was wrong by 1 year, one was wrong by 2 years and one was wrong by 4 years. What is the grandmother’s age?
questions.justification: Checking values like 77 or 79 against guesses 75, 78, 81 leads to multiple valid configurations or contradictions depending on the assignment of errors, leaving it indeterminate.

questions.content: The diagram shows a large rectangle ABCD divided into 12 identical small rectangles. What is the ratio AD/DC?
questions.justification: By setting width 'w' and height 'h' for small rectangles and equating side lengths of the composite rectangle, the ratio of the total sides AD/DC is 8/9.

questions.content: A rabbit and a hedgehog had a race around a 550 m long circular track. Both ran at constant speeds. The rabbit’s speed was 10 m/s, and the hedgehog’s speed was 1 m/s. They started at the same time. However, the hedgehog ran in the opposite direction to the rabbit. When they met, the hedgehog immediately turned round and ran after the rabbit. How long after the rabbit did the hedgehog reach the finish?
questions.justification: They meet at 50s. Rabbit has 5s to finish. Hedgehog turns back and must cover the 50m he already ran plus the 50m to the start? No, the calculation of relative paths shows he finishes 45s after Rabbit.

questions.content: The diagram shows square $PQRS$ of side-length 1. The midpoint of $RS$ is marked $U$ and the centre of the square is marked $W$. Line segments $TW$, $UW$ and $VW$ split the square into three regions of equal area. What is the length of $SV$?
questions.justification: Using the area formula for the polygons formed (triangles and quadrilaterals) and setting area = 1/3, SV is calculated as 5/6.

questions.content: There are three paths through our city park. A tree is planted in the middle of the park, as shown. What is the smallest number of trees that need to be planted so that there are the same number of trees on both sides of each of the paths?
questions.justification: The paths divide the park into regions. Balancing the counts around the three intersecting paths requires adding 3 trees in specific regions.

questions.content: Veronica has five rings on her fingers, as shown in the diagram. She takes them off one at a time. In how many different ways can she do this?
questions.justification: The order of removal is constrained by the stack on each finger. Calculating the permutations with these constraints gives 20 ways.

questions.content: Two congruent isosceles right-angled triangles each have a square inscribed, as shown in the diagram. The square marked P has an area of 45. What is the area of the square marked R?
questions.justification: The area of a square inscribed in a right isosceles triangle depends on its orientation. The ratio of the areas of the two types of inscribed squares is 8:9. Thus, 45 * (8/9) = 40.

questions.content: Eight teams participate in a football tournament. Each team plays against each other team exactly once. In each match, the winner gets 3 points and the loser does not get any points. If a match is drawn, each team gets 1 point. At the end of the tournament the total number of points obtained by all the teams is 61. What is the largest number of points that the champion team could have obtained?
questions.justification: Total games = 28. If all games were draws, points = 56. Each win adds 1 point to the total (3 vs 1+1). 61 - 56 = 5 wins. Max points for winner occurs with 5 wins and 2 draws = 17.

questions.content: A group of pirates divided 200 gold coins and 600 silver coins between them. Each officer received 5 gold and 10 silver coins. Each sailor received 3 gold and 8 silver coins. Each cabin boy received 1 gold and 6 silver coins. How many pirates are there in the group?
questions.justification: Solving the system 5x+3y+z=200 and 10x+8y+6z=600 results in x+y+z = 80.

questions.content: The squares on the surface of a 2 × 2 × 2 cube have one of three shapes on them. The shapes are either a circle or a square or an X sign. Any two squares that share a common side have different shapes on them. The picture shows one such possibility. Which of the following combinations of shapes is also possible on such a cube?

options.content: 6 circles, 8 squares and the rest are X’s
7 circles, 8 squares and the rest are X’s
5 circles, 8 squares and the rest are X’s
7 circles, 7 squares and the rest are X’s

questions.justification: The constraints of a 2x2x2 cube surface (24 squares) and the adjacency rules for 3 shapes make all the specific distributions A-D impossible.

questions.content: The inhabitants of a city always speak by means of questions. There are two types of inhabitants: the "positives", who always ask questions for which the answer is ”yes” and the ”negatives” who always ask questions for which the answer is ”no”. I met Albert and Berta and Berta asked me "Are Albert and I both negative?". What type of inhabitants are Albert and Berta?

options.content: There are not enough information to decide.

questions.justification: If Berta is Negative, her question must have a 'No' answer. 'No, we are not both negative' is true if Albert is Positive. This is consistent.

questions.content: A grocer has twelve different integer weights from 1 kg to 12 kg. She splits them into three groups of four weights each. The total weight of the first group is 41 kg and of the second is 26 kg. Which of the following weights is in the same group as the weight of 9 kg?
questions.justification: The only way to partition 1-12 into these sums places 9 and 7 in the same group (Group 1).

questions.content: The lengths of the diagonals of the squares ABCD and EFGB are 7 cm and 10 cm respectively. The point P is the intersection of the diagonals of the square ABCD. What is the area of the triangle FPD?
questions.justification: Using coordinate geometry with the centers and vertices derived from diagonal lengths, the area of triangle FPD is 17.5.

questions.content: The positive integer N is such that the product of its digits is 20. Which of the following could not be the product of the digits of N + 1?
questions.justification: Testing digit combinations for N (like 4,5 or 2,2,5) and calculating N+1 shows that 35 cannot be a product of the resulting digits.

questions.content: Five circles with centres A, B, C, D and E are arranged as shown in the diagram. Line segments are drawn to join the centres of adjacent circles. It is known that AB = 16 cm, BC = 14 cm, CD = 17 cm, DE = 13 cm, AE = 14 cm. Which point is the centre of the circle with the largest radius?
questions.justification: Solving the system rA+rB=16, rB+rC=14... gives rA=10, rB=6, rC=8, rD=9, rE=4. A is largest.

questions.content: A hole in the shape of a hemisphere is carved into each face of a cube. The holes are identical and centered at the centre of each face. The holes touch their neighbours at only one point. The cube has side 2. What is the diameter of each hole?
questions.justification: For hemispheres on adjacent faces to touch, the radius r must satisfy the geometry of the cube diagonal. The result for the diameter is √2.
